@NODE Configuration "Configuration"

@{b}Configuration@{ub}

RTN is configured via Workbench tooltypes. The possible entries and their
default values are listed below:

   ToolType       Default  Remark
   ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
   ScreenWidth    800      Width of TOC-Image
                           Possible values depend on your hardware configuration
   ScreenHeight   600      Height of TOC-Image
                           Possible values depend on your hardware configuration 
   ScreenDepth    16       Depth of RetinaScreen, TOC-Image is always 24 Bit
                           Possible values: 16, 24
   NoPerLine      6        Number of thumbnails per line
   FontName       CGTimes  Fontname for filenames, without extension '.font'
   FontSize       12       Size of font
   BackgroundR    80       Red component for background color.
                           Possible values: 0 - 255
   BackgroundG    80       Green component for background color
   BackgroundB    80       Blue component for background color
   SpacingR       120      Red component of spacing 
                           If the aspect of an image differs from that of the
                           TOC-file, there will be some space around the
                           thumnail.
                           Possible values: 0 - 255 
   SpacingG       120      Green component of spacing
   SpacingB       120      Blue component of spacing
   RetinaDisplay  DH0:Retina/RetinaTools/RetinaDisplay
                           Full path and filename of the displayer program
                           'RetinaDisplay' by MacroSystem
@ENDNODE

@NODE Start "Starting RTN"

@{b}Starting RTN@{ub}

RTN is started by simply double-clicking its icon. If you want to start the
program from CLI, you should keep the icon (RTN.info) in the directory where RTN
is located. Don't rename RTN, otherwise the icon won't be parsed correctly :-)

RTN uses RetinaEmu, and there might be a problem due to a bug in
retinaemu.library: If RTN produces no output, or even crashes, you should check
the settings for RTN in the Workbench-Emulation RetinaEmu. Don't use a Group for
RTN, simply choose a single screenmode like 800x600. You need not to change this
if you want to use a larger or smaller screen!
@ENDNODE

@NODE Help "Getting Help"

@{b}Getting Help@{ub}

If you run OS 3.0 (or better) then you can use the context-sensitive help
function of RTN. Simply click at the window (or part of it) and press the <Help>
key.

@ENDNODE

@NODE WI_main "Main Window"

@{b}Main Window@{ub}

In the main window you can load and display an old RTN-project, or you can
choose to create a new one.


   @{" Load a Project   " link WI_load }
   @{" Create a Project " link WI_create }
@ENDNODE

@NODE WI_load "Load Project"

@{b}Load Project@{ub}

'RTN File'
   Select an RTN-project for displaying via this gadget.

'Display'
   Click tis button to display a project. A RetinaEMU-screen will be opened and
   when the initialisation is complete you may click (left mouse button)
   on a thumbnail to display the full-size picture via RetinaDisplay. Pressing
   the right button once will quit RetinaDisplay and return to the RTN-project.
   You can leave the RTN-project-screen by pressing the right mouse button again.

'Jump to Screen'
   If you want to reuse an already loaded project, press this button. This will
   bring up again the project screen. Leave it by pressing the right mouse
   button.

'Close Screen'
   If you need to free some memory on your Retina board you may close a
   project-screen manually by clicking on this button. Normally this is not
   required, on program termination all memory is (hopefully) returned to the
   system.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WI_create "Create Project"

@{b}Create Project@{ub}

Here you can create a new RTN-Project.

      @{" List of Images   " link GR_create_1 }
      @{" Project Settings " link GR_create_2 }
      @{" Status           " link GR_create_3 }
@ENDNODE

@NODE GR_create_1 "List of Images"

@{b}List of Images@{ub}

'LST File'
   A list of images is an ASCII-file with the filename ending on '.LST'. It is
   specified either through the select-file-gadged or created for you
   automatically (see below). If you want to create a LST-file by hand, use your
   favourite editor and supply one image-file per line. If all the images are
   located in the same directory you need not to specify the full path. In the
   other case you have to.

'Base Path'
   If you have created a LST-file by hand and you did not supply the full path
   to the images, then here you can enter the path ending either on '/' or ':'.

'Create LST' 
   If you want to create a project of a whole dirctory just select the full path
   to this directory and press this button. The file-name of the LST-file will be
   '<name_of_directory>.LST'
@ENDNODE 

@NODE GR_create_2 "Project Settings"

@{b}Project Settings@{ub}

'RTN File'
   Specify a name for the new project

'ThumbNail Path'
   Give a path to a place where the thumbnails will be stored for later use.
   Only usefull if 'Save ThumbNails' is checked (see below). It is important
   that the path ends in '/' or ':'.

'Use Existing ThumbNails'
   If there already is a thumbnail for a specific picture in 'ThumbNail Path'
   it will be used if this button is checked. Important: If you change the
   tooltypes screenwidth, -height or number of thumbnails per line, the
   thumbnail-size changes. In this case it may be wise to delete the old
   thumbnails unless you want some SFX.

'Save ThumbNails'
   If this button is checked, the calculated thumbnails will be stored in the
   directory given in 'ThumbNail Path'.

'High Quality Scaling'
   RTN offers two algorithms to calculate the thumbnails. The one is quick (and
   dirty), the other one is not as fast but it produces really high quality
   output!
@ENDNODE 

@NODE GR_create_3 "Status"

@{b}Status@{ub}

'Create RTN'
   If all settings are choosen appropriate you can start calculation by pressing
   this gadget. A RetinaEMU-screen will be opened and the LST-file will be
   parsed line by line.Depending on the amount of images to be computed, RTN
   will create one or more .TOC-files and .RTN-files. These files may be moved
   to any directory as long as the .RTN-file and the .TOC-file stay together and
   as long as you used absolute paths to the images in the .LST-file. The
   output-format of the .TOC-files is IFF DEEP (24 bit). Later you can convert
   them into any format supported by RTN (JPEG recommended).

'Jump to Screen'
   If you want to reuse an already loaded project, press this button. This will
   bring up again the project screen. Leave it by pressing the right mouse
   button.

'Close Screen'
   If you need to free some memory on your Retina board you may close a
   project-screen manually by clicking on this button. Normally this is not
   required, on program termination all memory is (hopefully) returned to the
   system. 

In the status text-field some messages are displayed so you can watch RTN making
progress. If an error occures, it will be written down in 'RTN.log', a fatal
error will bring up a message-window and break execution.
@ENDNODE 

@NODE Problems "Common Problems"

@{b}Common Problems@{ub}

If RTN produces no output, or even crashes:
   RTN uses RetinaEmu, and there might be a problem due to a bug in
   retinaemu.library. You should check the settings for RTN in the Workbench
   Emulation RetinaEmu. Don't use a Group for RTN, simply choose a single
   screenmode like 800x600. You need not to change this if you want to use a
   larger or smaller screen!

You click on a thumbnail, but the fullscale picture isn't displayed:
   Check the tooltype 'RetinaDisplay'. It should contain the full path and the
   filename of the displayer program RetinaDisplay.
@ENDNODE

